rVsowz4cndSa9uDE6UHVYJPmH-46ORmbQHBQrEluT1ZyYoaFIcHqd4a-2P0YRNY38PMtNeUgc-aC8g61UbZj0BnEfYPWbITdfz-\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test resources for JDBC**\\n\\nI’m thinking about creating test resources for the JDBC jar to include the correct classpath. It seems like the search involves the parent of every classpath entry along with a specific jdbc path. The resources should be structured under build/classes/java/test or build/resources/test. Maybe there's a way to add test resources, ensuring the jdbc directory is there before static initialization. It might be easier to commit the binary jar, but I’m also weighing the idea of including source for a fake MySQL driver class for testing.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Setting up JDBC test driver**\\n\\nI’m considering creating a directory named `mysql-connector-java-test-driver` under a jdbc subdirectory that includes the `Driver.class` file. At runtime, I wonder if I can copy class file bytes from the test classpath. For native runtime, dynamic loading might not work, but perhaps regular JVM can execute tests during the native-image build. The dynamic access report is generated after nativeTestCompile, so I’ll check the tool plugin. Alternatively, I could include a fake driver source under `src/test/java`, ensuring the context classloader has access to it. It's a lot to juggle!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Creating test source for Driver**\\n\\nI might create the test source for `com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver`, but it seems like the compiled class ends up in `build/classes/java/test/com/mysql/cj/jdbc/Driver.class`, which isn't under `jdbc/mysql`. I need to ensure it’s structured correctly so that everything aligns with my classpath expectations. There’s some juggling to do with the directories to make sure the test resources are all accessible during runtime. It's a bit tricky, but I’m working through it!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_EfpTwk8Pwx0J